<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Port of Tilbury response to</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Freshwater UK on behalf of The Port of Tilbury</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Port of Tilbury (the P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or Tilbury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> believes that the proposed designation of the tidal Thames as a marine conservation zones (MCZ) will impact on the Port and other river operators’ ability to attract international investment to the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When attempting to balance the three pillars of sustainability, it is important that decisions do not jeopardise national economic output and the forward investment programme required to maintain that vital activity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If designated, the proposed 58-mile MCZ for the tidal Thames would run from Richmond</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Southend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. As it stands, this would encompass the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort’s riverside operations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, alongside the many existing environmental designations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The three species the designation is seeking to safeguard are protected </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">under existing legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Port looks to the Government’s rejection of the proposed blanket Stour and Orwell e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stuaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> MCZ designations – in-and-around Harwich and Felixstowe ports – on economic grounds and argues that a strong precedent has been established for a rejection of the proposed Thames MCZ. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Port has been represented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">throughout the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> MCZ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> identification process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by tidal Thames’ conservancy authority, the Port of London Authority (the PLA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The PLA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has had a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">presence at l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal Thames meetings, regional Balanced Seas oversight groups</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, industry groups and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">direct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">representations to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (DEFRA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Port of Tilbury o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">verview</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tilbury is a port built upon a diverse portfolio: the UK’s leading port for handling paper and forest products; home to Britain's largest grain terminal and the third biggest container operation in the country with a thriving cruise terminal facility for Baltic and northern European destinations. The Port is one of the UK’s largest, covering over 850 acres and employing, with their customers, 3,500 people (10% of all employment in the borough of Thurrock).</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Port</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is where London’s docks moved to after the Second World War. This move was eventually followed by the successful trust port privatisation of Tilbury Docks in 1991 and its commercial success story today. In 2011, the Port celebrated its 125th birthday.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alongside Tilbury, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Forth Ports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ltd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">owns and operates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seven other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ports in the UK: Dundee, Leith, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Grangemouth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Kirkcaldy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Methil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Burntisland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Rosyth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Forth Ports has made substantial investments in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Port </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">since its purchase. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">£95m </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">purchase of Tilbury Container Services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, its overhaul and enhancement combined with the large </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">multi-million pound </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">extension to the port estate to provide significant additional warehousing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and logistics facilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> attract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> further business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">tidal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Thames</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: balancing the three pillars of sustainability</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Thames is a dynamic environment and has acted as a catalyst for centuries of growth – providing the UK economy with the necessary goods to sustain the population and means by which the economy can grow. The river has accommodated industry and wildlife side-by-side to great effect. In fact, with current environmental designations animals, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">birds, fish </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s have thrived in recent years.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The benefits of designating the Thames as an MCZ are unclear as the species its designation proposed to protect are already protected under existing legislation:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Smelt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – UKBAP priority species and protected under the Marine and Coastal Access Act</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Tentacled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> Lagoon Worm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – Schedule 5 protected species under the Wildlife and Countryside Act</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">European Eel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – UKBAP priority species, managed under Thames Eel Management Plan</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">habitats </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for these species on the Thames are all designated as being in favourable condition; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all of the habitats and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">species are found elsewhere in the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remains uneasy about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DEFRA’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">decision to require further study of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposal for a Thames MCZ. This unease is compounded by the precedent set by the decision to eliminate the proposed MCZ designations on the Stour and Orwell e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stuaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Port</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the view</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stated in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DEFRA consultation document, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Marine Conservation Zones: Consultation on proposals for designation in 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Annex A3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that such a designation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the Thames </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would result in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘significant un-quantified socio-economic implications associated with development in the estuary’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Port believes that the sentiments reflected in DEFRA’s evaluation of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stour and Orwell e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stuaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> MCZ designation is equally applicable to the tidal Thames: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘...</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the presence of a number of other national and international environmental designations in the area and the environmental stewardship provided by port and harbour authorities and others, we have decided not to proceed with designation of this site</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.’</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There remains no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">costed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> impact analysis of the potential economic impact of MCZ designation on the Thames. This data is essential to a properly informed debate balancing all elements of sustainability. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DEFRA guidance requires that all elements of sustainability are considered.  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Guidance on selection and designation of Marine Conservation Zones</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (Note 1), September 2010 says:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘…</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it will be desirable to avoid designating MCZs that would be detrimental to ongoing, licensed or planned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">socio-economic activities…</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Where there may be irreconcilable conflicts between socio-economic activities and MCZs, then suitable alternati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve sites should be considered.’</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Uncertainty around the designation of a Thames MCZ will increasingly become a factor in the decision making process around investment plans for new or improved riverside cargo handling facilities.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the absence of a clear position, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort’s commercial decisions will be informed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by the I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mpact Assessment for the Thames (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Annex 1 from Finding Sanctuary, Irish Sea Conservation Zones, Net Gain and Balanced Seas. 2012. Impact Assessment materials in support of the Regional Marine Conservation Zone Projects’ Recommendations), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which says</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Additional costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will be incurred as a result’ for future licence applications for navigational dredging plans or proposals within 1 km of this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rMCZ</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘Unknown </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">potentially significant costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of mitigation could arise,’ for future licence applications.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-alig