style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposed 58-mile blanket designation of the tidal Thames would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">create a barrier to investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n the busiest UK inland waterway and Britain’s second largest port.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The three species the designation is seeking to safeguard are protected </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">under existing legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aforementioned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">investment decisions are not taken lightly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and, within a group of ports owned by an infrastructure fund with an international portfolio of assets, competition for investment capital is fierce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Anything tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t unnecessarily undermines the P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort’s operating environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would weaken our position and, for the good of UK plc,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should be avoided </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at all costs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort’s investment programme is playing a central role in delivering growth to the Thames Gatewa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y and Thurrock area.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The uncertainty around the extent of the proposed Thames MCZ, what </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">designation will mean in practice and what will happen to the overlapping environmental legislat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion/designations is concerning.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Port believes the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evidence base for designation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is unduly skewed towards locations of economic activity, as these marine environments are the best and most surveyed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There needs to be a balanced approach that takes full and demonstrable account of all the pillars of sustainability – environmental, economic and social sides of the argument – in any evaluation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">24 January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">3</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>